# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: software-bill-of-materials-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] To find the right level of component granularity, software architects have to continuously iterate their component designs with developers.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] Architects need to take into account user requirements, responsibilities, and architectural characteristics.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] CBSE grew out of earlier paradigms such as structured programming and object-oriented programming, but it places greater emphasis on building software by assembling and integrating pre-existing components.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] Unlike objects, which typically encapsulate both data and behavior, components are higher-level constructs that provide well-defined interfaces and can be deployed independently.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] Component orientation underlies many modern software frameworks and architectural styles, including service-oriented architecture (SOA), microservices, and widely used frontend frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] For large-scale systems developed by large teams, a disciplined culture and process is required to achieve the benefits of CBSE.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] Third-party components are often utilized in large systems, raising issues of integration, licensing, and software quality.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] The system can be designed visually with the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] Each component is shown as a rectangle, and an interface is shown as a lollipop to indicate a provided interface and as a socket to indicate consumption of an interface.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] This graphical representation helps clarify the relationships and dependencies between components.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/component-based-software-engineering] Component-based usability testing is applied when components interact directly with the end user, ensuring both functionality and user experience are preserved when components are reused or replaced.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open-source software development can bring in diverse perspectives beyond those of a single company.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] A 2024 estimate of the value of open-source software to firms is $8.8 trillion, as firms would need to spend 3.5 times the amount they currently do without the use of open source software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The Open Source Initiative's (OSI) definition is recognized by several governments internationally as the standard or *de facto* definition.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] OSI uses *The Open Source Definition* to determine whether it considers a software license open source.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The definition was based on the Debian Free Software Guidelines, written and adapted primarily by Bruce Perens.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Perens did not base his writing on the "four freedoms" from the Free Software Foundation (FSF), which were only widely available later.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Under Perens' definition, *open source* is a broad software license that makes source code available to the general public with relaxed or non-existent restrictions on the use and modification of the code.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] It is an explicit "feature" of open source that it puts very few restrictions on the use or distribution by any organization or user, in order to enable the rapid evolution of the software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Despite initially accepting it, Richard Stallman of the FSF now flatly opposes the term "Open Source" being applied to what they refer to as "free software".
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Although he agrees that the two terms describe "almost the same category of software", Stallman considers equating the terms incorrect and misleading.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Stallman also opposes the professed pragmatism of the Open Source Initiative, as he fears that the free software ideals of freedom and community are threatened by compromising on the FSF's idealistic standards for software freedom.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The FSF considers free software to be a subset of open-source software, and Richard Stallman explained that DRM software, for example, can be developed as open source, despite that it does not give its users freedom (it restricts them), and thus does not qualify as free software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In his 1997 essay *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*, open-source influential contributor Eric S.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Raymond suggests a model for developing OSS known as the *bazaar* model.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Raymond likens the development of software by traditional methodologies to building a cathedral, with careful isolated work by individuals or small groups.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] He suggests that all software should be developed using the bazaar style, with differing agendas and approaches.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In the traditional model of development, which he called the *cathedral* model, development takes place in a centralized way.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Roles include people dedicated to designing (the architects), people responsible for managing the project, and people responsible for implementation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Traditional software engineering follows the cathedral model.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The bazaar model, however, is different.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In this model, roles are not clearly defined.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The process of Open source development begins with a requirements elicitation where developers consider if they should add new features or if a bug needs to be fixed in their project.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] This is established by communicating with the OSS community through avenues such as bug reporting and tracking or mailing lists and project pages.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Next, OSS developers select or are assigned to a task and identify a solution.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Because there are often many different possible routes for solutions in OSS, the best solution must be chosen with careful consideration and sometimes even peer feedback.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The developer then begins to develop and commit the code.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The code is then tested and reviewed by peers.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Developers can edit and evolve their code through feedback from continuous integration.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Once the leadership and community are satisfied with the whole project, it can be partially released and user instruction can be documented.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] If the project is ready to be released, it is frozen, with only serious bug fixes or security repairs occurring.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Finally, the project is fully released and only changed through minor bug fixes.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open source implementation of a standard can increase the adoption and long-term viability of that standard.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] It often fosters developer loyalty, as contributors feel a greater sense of participation and ownership in the development process and the end product.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Moreover, lower costs of marketing and logistical services are needed for OSS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] OSS can be a tool to promote a company's image, including its commercial products.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The OSS development approach has been known to some to help produce reliable, high quality software quickly and inexpensively.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open source development offers the potential to quicken innovation and create social value.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In France, for instance, a policy that incentivized government to favor free open-source software increased to nearly 600,000 OSS contributions per year, generating social value by increasing the quantity and quality of open-source software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] This policy also led to an estimated increase of up to 18% of tech startups and a 14% increase in the number of people employed in the IT sector.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] OSS can be highly reliable when it has thousands of independent programmers testing and fixing bugs of the software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open source is not dependent on the company or author that originally created it.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Even if the company fails, the code continues to exist and be developed by its users.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] OSS is flexible as modular systems allow programmers to build custom interfaces or add new abilities to it.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The mix of divergent perspectives, corporate objectives, and personal goals allows innovation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Moreover, free software can be developed in accordance with purely technical requirements.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] It does not require thinking about commercial pressure that often degrades the quality of the software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Commercial pressures make traditional software developers pay more attention to customers' requirements than to security requirements, since such features are somewhat invisible to the customer.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In open-source software development, tools are used to support the development of the product and the development process itself.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Version control systems such as Centralized Version control system (CVCS) and the distributed version control system (DVCS) are examples of tools, often open source, that help manage the source code files and the changes to those files for a software project in order to foster collaboration.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] CVCS are centralized with a central repository while DVCS are decentralized and have a local repository for every user.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Concurrent Versions System (CVS) and later Subversion (SVN) are examples of CVCS, whereas Git is a DVCS and the most widely used version control software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The repositories are hosted and published on source-code-hosting facilities such as GitHub or Gitlab.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open-source projects use utilities such as issue trackers to organize open-source software development.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Commonly used bug trackers include Bugzilla and Redmine.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Tools such as mailing lists and IRC provide means of coordination and discussion of bugs among developers.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Project web pages, wiki pages, roadmap lists and newsgroups allow for the distribution of project information that focuses on end users.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The basic roles OSS participants can fall into multiple categories, beginning with leadership at the center of the project who have control over its execution.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Next are the core contributors with a great deal of experience and authority in the project who may guide the other contributors.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Non-core contributors have less experience and authority, but regularly contribute and are vital to the project's development.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] New contributors are the least experienced but with mentorship and guidance can become regular contributors.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Some possible ways of contributing to open-source software include such roles as programming, maintaining, user interface design and testing, web design, bug triage, accessibility design and testing, UX design, code testing, and security review and testing.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, there are several ways of contributing to OSS projects even without coding skills.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For example, some less technical ways of participating are documentation writing and editing, translation, project management, event organization and coordination, marketing, release management, community management, and public relations and outreach.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Funding is another way that individuals and organizations choose to contribute to open source projects.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Groups like Open Collective provide a means for individuals to contribute monthly to supporting their favorite projects.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Organizations like the Sovereign Tech Fund is able to contribute to millions to supporting the tools the German Government uses.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The National Science Foundation established a Pathways to Enable Open-Source Ecosystems (POSE) program to support open source innovation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The adoption of open-source software by industry is increasing over time.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] OSS is popular in several industries such as telecommunications, aerospace, healthcare, and media & entertainment due to the benefits it provides.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Adoption of OSS is more likely in larger organizations and is dependent on the company's IT usage, operating efficiencies, and the productivity of employees.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Industries are likely to use OSS due to back-office functionality, sales support, research and development, software features, quick deployment, portability across platforms and avoidance of commercial license management.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Additionally, lower cost for hardware and ownership are also important benefits.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Organizations that contribute to the development and expansions of free and open-source software movements exist all over the world.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] These organizations are dedicated to goals such as teaching and spreading technology.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] As listed by a former vice president of the Open Source Initiative, some American organizations include the Free Software Foundation, Software Freedom Conservancy, the Open Source Initiative and Software in the Public Interest.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Within Europe some notable organizations are Free Software Foundation Europe, open-source projects EU (OSP) and OpenForum Europe (OFE).
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] One Australian organization is Linux Australia while Asia has Open source Asia and FOSSAsia.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Free and open source software for Africa (FOSSFA) and OpenAfrica are African organizations and Central and South Asia has such organizations as FLISOL and GRUP de usuarios de software libre Peru.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Outside of these, many more organizations dedicated to the advancement of open-source software exist.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] FOSS products are generally licensed under two types of licenses: permissive licensing and copyleft licensing.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Both of these types of licenses are different than proprietary licensing in that they can allow more users access to the software and allow for the creation of derivative works as specified by the terms of the specific license, as each license has its own rules.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Permissive licenses allow recipients of the software to implement the author's copyright rights without having to use the same license for distribution.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Examples of this type of license include the BSD, MIT, and Apache licenses.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Copyleft licenses are different in that they require recipients to use the same license for at least some parts of the distribution of their works.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Strong copyleft licenses require all derivative works to use the same license while weak copyleft licenses require the use of the same license only under certain conditions.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Examples of this type of license include the GNU family of licenses, and the MPL and EPL licenses.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The similarities between these two categories of licensing include that they provide a broad grant of copyright rights, require that recipients preserve copyright notices, and that a copy of the license is provided to recipients with the code.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] One important legal precedent for open-source software was created in 2008, when the Jacobson v Katzer case enforced terms of the Artistic license, including attribution and identification of modifications.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The ruling of this case cemented enforcement under copyright law when the conditions of the license were not followed.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Because of the similarity of the Artistic license to other open-source software licenses, the ruling created a precedent that applied widely.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Examples of free-software license / open-source licenses include Apache licenses, BSD licenses, GNU General Public Licenses, GNU Lesser General Public License, MIT License, Eclipse Public License and Mozilla Public License.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Several gray areas exist within software regulation that have great impact on open-source software, such as if software is a good or service, what can be considered a modification, governance through contract vs license, ownership and right of use.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] While there have been developments on these issues, they often lead to even more questions.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The existence of these uncertainties in regulation has a negative impact on industries involved in technologies as a whole.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Within the legal history of software as a whole, there was much debate on whether to protect it as intellectual property under patent law, copyright law or establishing a unique regulation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Ultimately, copyright law became the standard with computer programs being considered a form of literary work, with some tweaks of unique regulation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Software is generally considered source code and object code, with both being protectable, though there is legal variety in this definition.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Some jurisdictions attempt to expand or reduce this conceptualization for their own purposes.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For example, The European Court of Justice defines a computer program as not including the functionality of a program, the programming language, or the format of data files.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] By limiting protections of the different aspects of software, the law favors an open-source approach to software use.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The US especially has an open approach to software, with most open-source licenses originating there.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, this has increased the focus on patent rights within these licenses, which has seen backlash from the OSS community, who prefer other forms of IP protection.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Another issue includes technological protection measures (TPM) and digital rights management (DRM) techniques which were internationally legally recognized and protected in the 1996 World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) Treaty.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open source software proponents disliked these technologies as they constrained end-users potentially beyond copyright law.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Europe responded to such complaints by putting TPM under legal controls, representing a victory for OSS supporters.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In open-source communities, instead of owning the software produced, the producer owns the development of the evolving software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In this way, the future of the software is open, making ownership or intellectual property difficult within OSS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Licensing and branding can prevent others from stealing it, preserving its status as a public good.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open source software can be considered a public good as it is available to everyone and does not decrease in value for others when downloaded by one person.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open source software is unique in that it becomes more valuable as it is used and contributed to, instead of diminishing the resource.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] This is explained by concepts such as investment in reputation and network effects.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The economic model of open-source software can be explained as developers contribute work to projects, creating public benefits.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Developers choose projects based on the perceived benefits or costs, such as improved reputation or value of the project.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The motivations of developers can come from many different places and reasons, but the important takeaway is that money is not the only or even most important incentivization.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Because economic theory mainly focuses on the consumption of scarce resources, the OSS dynamic can be hard to understand.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In OSS, producers become consumers by reaping the rewards of contributing to a project.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For example, a developer becomes well regarded by their peers for a successful contribution to an OSS project.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The social benefits and interactions of OSS are difficult to account for in economic models as well.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Furthermore, the innovation of technology creates constantly changing value discussions and outlooks, making economic model unable to predict social behavior.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Although OSS is theoretically challenging in economic models, it is explainable as a sustainable social activity that requires resources.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] These resources include time, money, technology and contributions.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Many developers have used technology funded by organizations such as universities and governments, though these same organizations benefit from the work done by OSS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] As OSS grows, hybrid systems containing OSS and proprietary systems are becoming more common.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Throughout the mid 2000s, more and more tech companies have begun to use OSS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For example, Dell's move of selling computers with Linux already installed.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Microsoft itself has launched a Linux-based operating system despite previous animosity with the OSS movement.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Despite these developments, these companies tend to only use OSS for certain purposes, leading to worries that OSS is being taken advantage of by corporations and not given anything in return.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, an issue to be considered is cybersecurity.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] While accidental vulnerabilities are possible, so are attacks by outside agents.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Because of these fears, governmental interest in contributing to the governance of software has become more prominent.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, these are the broad strokes of the issue, with each country having their own specific politicized interactions with open-source software and their goals for its implementation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] These criteria include whether it comes from and is maintained by trusted sources, whether it will continue to be maintained, if there are dependencies on sub-components in the software, component security and integrity, and foreign governmental influence.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Another issue for governments in regard to open source is their investments in technologies such as operating systems, semiconductors, cloud, and artificial intelligence.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] These technologies all have implications for global cooperation, again opening up security issues and political consequences.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Many countries have to balance technological innovation with technological dependence in these partnerships.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For example, after China's open-source dependent company Huawei was prevented from using Google's Android system in 2019, they began to create their own alternative operating system: Harmony OS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Germany recently established a Sovereign Tech Fund, to help support the governance and maintenance of the software that they use.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In the early days of computing, particularly during the 1950s and 1960s, programmers and developers commonly shared software to learn from one another and advance the field.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Early systems such as Unix even provided users with access to their source code, allowing collaboration and modification.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, with the rise of the commercial software industry in the 1970s and 1980s, this culture of open sharing began to decline as proprietary models became dominant.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Despite this shift, academic and research institutions continued to promote collaborative software development practices.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In response, the open-source movement was born out of the work of skilled programmer enthusiasts, widely referred to as hackers or hacker culture.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] One of these enthusiasts, Richard Stallman, was a driving force behind the free software movement, which would later allow for the open-source movement.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In 1984, he resigned from MIT to create a free operating system, GNU, after the programmer culture in his lab was stifled by proprietary software preventing source code from being shared and improved upon.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] GNU was UNIX compatible, meaning that the programmer enthusiasts would still be familiar with how it worked.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, it quickly became apparent that there was some confusion with the label Stallman had chosen of free software, which he described as free as in free speech, not free beer, referring to the meaning of free as freedom rather than price.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] He later expanded this concept of freedom to the four essential freedoms.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Through GNU, open-source norms of incorporating others' source code, community bug fixes and suggestions of code for new features appeared.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In 1985, Stallman founded the Free Software Foundation (FSF) to promote changes in software and to help write GNU.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In order to prevent his work from being used in proprietary software, Stallman created the concept of copyleft, which allowed the use of his work by anyone, but under specific terms.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] To do this, he created the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL) in 1989, which was updated in 1991.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In 1991, GNU was combined with the Linux kernel written by Linus Torvalds, as a kernel was missing in GNU.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The operating system is now usually referred to as Linux.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] As free software developed, the Free Software Foundation began to look how to bring free software ideas and perceived benefits to the commercial software industry.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] It was concluded that FSF's social activism was not appealing to companies and they needed a way to rebrand the free software movement to emphasize the business potential of sharing and collaborating on software source code.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The term open source was suggested by Christine Peterson in 1998 at a meeting of supporters of free software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Many in the group felt the name free software was confusing to newcomers and holding back industry interest and they readily accepted the new designation of open source, creating the Open Source Initiative (OSI) and the OSI definition of what open source software is.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The Open Source Initiative's (OSI) definition is now recognized by several governments internationally as the standard or *de facto* definition.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The OSI definition differed from the free software definition in that it allows the inclusion of proprietary software and allows more liberties in its licensing.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Some, such as Stallman, agree more with the original concept of free software as a result because it takes a strong moral stance against proprietary software, though there is much overlap between the two movements in terms of the operation of the software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, while free and open-source software (FOSS) has historically played a role outside of mainstream private software development, companies as large as Microsoft have begun to develop official open source presences on the Internet.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] IBM, Oracle, and State Farm are just a few of the companies with a serious public stake in today's competitive open source market, marking a significant shift in the corporate philosophy concerning the development of FOSS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The future of the open source software community, and the free software community by extension, has become successful if not confused about what it stands for.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For example, Android and Ubuntu are examples milestones of success in the open source software rise to prominence from the sidelines of technological innovation as it existed in the early 2000s.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The use of OSS has become more common in business with 78% of companies reporting that they run all or part of their operations on FOSS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The popularity of OSS has risen to the point that Microsoft, a once detractor of OSS, has included its use in their systems.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, this success has raised concerns that will determine the future of OSS as the community must answer questions such as what OSS is, what should it be, and what should be done to protect it, if it even needs protecting.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] All in all, while the free and open source revolution has slowed to a perceived equilibrium in the market place, that does not mean it is over as many theoretical discussions must take place to determine its future.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open source software differs from proprietary software in that it is publicly available, the license requires no fees, modifications and distributions are allowed under license specifications.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] All of this works to prevent a monopoly on any OSS product, which is a goal of proprietary software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Proprietary software limits their customers' choices to either committing to using that software, upgrading it or switching to other software, forcing customers to have their software preferences impacted by their monetary cost.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The ideal case scenario for the proprietary software vendor would be a lock-in, where the customer does not or cannot switch software due to these costs and continues to buy products from that vendor.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Within proprietary software, bug fixes can only be provided by the vendor, moving platforms requires another purchase and the existence of the product relies on the vendor, who can discontinue it at any point.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Additionally, proprietary software does not provide its source code and cannot be altered by users.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For businesses, this can pose a security risk and source of frustration, as they cannot specialize the product to their needs, and there may be hidden threats or information leaks within the software that they cannot access or change.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Under OSI's definition, open source is a broad software license that makes source code available to the general public with relaxed or non-existent restrictions on the use and modification of the code.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] It is an explicit feature of open source that it puts very few restrictions on the use or distribution by any organization or user, in order to enable the rapid evolution of the software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Richard Stallman, leader of the Free software movement and member of the free software foundation opposes the term open source being applied to what they refer to as free software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Although he agrees that the two terms describe almost the same category of software, Stallman considers equating the terms incorrect and misleading.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] He believes that the main difference is that by choosing one term over the other lets others know about what one's goals are: development (open source) or a social stance (free software).
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Nevertheless, there is significant overlap between open source software and free software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The FSF considers free software to be a subset of open-source software, and Richard Stallman explained that DRM software, for example, can be developed as open source, despite how it restricts its users, and thus does not qualify as free software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The FSF said that the term open source fosters an ambiguity of a different kind such that it confuses the mere availability of the source with the freedom to use, modify, and redistribute it.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] On the other hand, the term free software was criticized for the ambiguity of the word free, which was seen as discouraging for business adoption, and for the historical ambiguous usage of the term.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Developers have used the alternative terms *Free and Open Source Software* (FOSS), or *Free/Libre and Open Source Software* (FLOSS), consequently, to describe open-source software that is also free software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Software can be distributed with source code, which is a code that is readable.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Software is source available when this source code is available to be seen.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However to be source available or FOSS, the source code does not need to be accessible to all, just the users of that software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] While all FOSS software is source available because this is a requirement made by the Open Source Definition, not all source available software is FOSS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For example, if the software does not meet other aspects of the Open Source Definition such as permitted modification or redistribution, even if the source code is available, the software is not FOSS.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] A recent trend within software companies is open-sourcing, or transitioning their previous proprietary software into open-source software through releasing it under an open-source license.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Examples of companies who have done this are Google, Microsoft and Apple.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Additionally, open-sourcing can refer to programming open-source software or installing open-source software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open-sourcing can be beneficial in multiple ways, such as attracting more external contributors who bring new perspectives and problem solving capabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The downsides of open-sourcing include the work that has to be done to maintaining the new community, such as making the base code easily understandable, setting up communication channels for new developers and creating documentation to allow new developers to easily join.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, a review of several open-sourced projects found that although a newly open-sourced project attracts many newcomers, a great amount are likely to soon leave the project and their forks are also likely to not be impactful.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Other concepts that may share some similarities to open source are shareware, public domain software, freeware, and software viewers/readers that are freely available but do not provide source code.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, these differ from open source software in access to source code, licensing, copyright and fees.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Despite being able to collaborate internationally, open source software contributors were found to mostly be located in large clusters such as Silicon Valley that largely collaborate within themselves.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Possible reasons for this phenomenon may be that the OSS contributor demographic largely works in software, meaning that the OSS geographic location is closely related to that dispersion and collaborations could be encouraged through work and social networks.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Code acceptance can be impacted by status within these social network clusters, creating unfair predispositions in code acceptance based on location.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Barriers to international collaboration also include linguistic or cultural differences.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Furthermore, each country has been shown to have a higher acceptance rate for code from contributors within their country except India, indicating a bias for culturally similar collaborators.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In 2021, the countries with the highest open source software contributions included the United States, China, Germany, India, and the UK, in that order.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The countries with the highest OSS developers per capita from a study in 2021 include, in order, Iceland, Switzerland, Norway, Sweden, and Finland, while in 2008 the countries with top amount of estimated contributors in SourceForge were the United States, Germany, United Kingdom, Canada and France.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Though there have been several studies done on the distribution and contributions of OSS developers, this is still an open field that can be measured in several different ways.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For instance, Information and communication technology participation, population, wealth and proportion of access to the internet have been shown to be correlated with OSS contributions.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Although gender diversity has been found to enhance team productivity, women still face biases while contributing to open source software projects when their gender is identifiable.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In 2002, only 1.5% of international open-source software developers were women, while women made up 28% of tech industry roles, demonstrating their low representation in the software field.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, a more recent figure of female OSS participation internationally calculated across 2005 to 2021 is 9.8%, with most being recent contributors, indicating that female participation may be growing.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Contributors to OSS are motivated by belief in FOSS philosophy, personal interests, caring about the community, interest in projects and problem-solving, etc.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] In addition, users of a given software may also contribute as a way of improving tools they use, while others are drawn to the collaborative nature of open-source development environments.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Also, engagement with active projects allow contributors to stay current with industry practices and emerging trends.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The open source projects include the innovations and trends and they make it popular within the tech field.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Contributing to OSS can also increase a contributor's visibility and reputation within the community, as contributions are publicly accessible and can be reviewed by others.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] As a result, thousands of contributors daily contribute to the open source projects and help maintain it for the improvement of general public.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Even though programming was originally seen as a female profession, there remains a large gap in computing.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Social identity tends to be a large concern as women in the tech industry face insecurity about attracting unwanted male attention and harassment or being unfeminine in their technology knowledge, having a large impact on confidence.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Some male tech participants make clear that they believe women fitting in within the culture is impossible, furthering the insecurity for women and their place in the tech industry.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Additionally, even in a voluntary contribution environment like open source software, women tend to end up doing the less technical aspects of projects, such as manual testing or documentation despite women and men showing the same productivity in OSS contributions.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Explicit biases include longer feedback time, more scrutinization of code and lower acceptance rate of code.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Specifically in the open-source software community, women report that sexually offensive language is common and the women's identity as female is given more attention that as an OSS contributor.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Bias is hard to address due to the belief that gender should not matter, with most contributors feeling that women getting special treatment is unfair and success should be dependent on skill, preventing any changes to be more inclusive.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open source software projects are built and maintained by a network of programmers, who may often be volunteers, and are widely used in free as well as commercial products.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] While the term open source applied originally only to the source code of software, it is now being applied to many other areas such as open-source ecology, a movement to decentralize technologies so that any human can use them.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] However, it is often misapplied to other areas that have different and competing principles, which overlap only partially.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The same principles that underlie open-source software can be found in many other ventures, such as open source, open content, and open collaboration.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] This "culture" or ideology takes the view that the principles apply more generally to facilitate concurrent input of different agendas, approaches, and priorities, in contrast with more centralized models of development such as those typically used in commercial companies.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] More than 90 percent of companies use open-source software as a component of their proprietary software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] The decision to use open-source software, or even engage with open-source projects to improve existing open-source software, is typically a pragmatic business decision.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] When proprietary software is in direct competition with an open-source alternative, research has found conflicting results on the effect of the competition on the proprietary product's price and quality.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] For decades, some companies have made servicing of an open-source software product for enterprise users their business model.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] These companies control an open-source software product, and instead of charging for licensing or use, charge for improvements, integration, and other servicing.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Software as a service (SaaS) products based on open-source components are increasingly common.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/open-source-software] Open-source software is preferred for scientific applications, because it increases transparency and aids in the validation and acceptance of scientific results.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] A **software supply chain** is the components, libraries, tools, and processes used to develop, build, and publish a software artifact.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] A **software bill of materials** (**SBOM**) declares the inventory of components used to build a software artifact, including any open source and proprietary software components.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] It is the software analogue to the traditional manufacturing BOM, which is used as part of supply chain management.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] SBOMs are a strategy for improving transparency in the software supply chain.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] Software supply chain attacks compromise an upstream component — such as a widely-used library, a build tool, or a distribution channel — in order to simultaneously affect all downstream users of that component.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] High-profile incidents such as the SolarWinds attack illustrated the scale and reach of such attacks.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] Researchers have catalogued the attack surface into a taxonomy covering all stages from source-code contribution to package distribution, linking attack vectors to real-world incidents and corresponding safeguards.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] Another important concept in software supply chains is provenance: signed attestations can record where a software artifact came from, which source and dependencies were used, and which steps in the build pipeline produced it.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] Provenance frameworks such as in-toto help downstream users verify that a release was built by an expected process and help detect tampering between source retrieval, build, and distribution.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] An SBOM allows builders to make sure open-source and third-party software components are up to date and respond quickly to new vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] Buyers and other stakeholders can use an SBOM to perform vulnerability or license analysis, which can be used to evaluate and manage risk in a product.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] While many companies use a spreadsheet for general BOM management, there are additional risks and issues in an SBOM written to a spreadsheet, such as the inability to automatically enrich it with vulnerability data or integrate it into security toolchains.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] It is best practice for SBOMs to be collectively stored in a repository that can be part of other automation systems and easily queried by other applications.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] Cybersecurity transparency studies, including TRACS 2025, identify the availability of SBOMs as one of the criteria used when purchasing information security solutions.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] However, not all enterprise security products provide publicly available SBOMs.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] Research on open-source ecosystems indicates that policy-driven SBOMs remain rare in practice: one large-scale study found that only about 0.56% of popular GitHub repositories contain SBOMs created in accordance with formal security or compliance policies.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] Also, according to other research, fewer than half of tested software projects include SBOMs in their releases, and many of those SBOMs are incomplete or do not fully conform to established standards.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] At the same time, corporate-level surveys report that approximately 60–76 % of enterprises require SBOMs from suppliers or have integrated SBOMs into procurement and supply-chain risk management processes.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] US President Joe Biden’s **Executive Order 14028 on Improving the Nation’s Cybersecurity** of May 12, 2021 ordered NIST and NTIA to lay down guidelines for software supply chain management, including for SBOMs.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-bill-of-materials] The "automation support" requirement specifies the need for "automatic generation," which is possible with the use of Software Composition Analysis (SCA) solutions.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The original purpose of SPDX was to improve license compliance, and it has since been expanded to facilitate additional use cases such as supply-chain transparency and security.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] SPDX is authored by the community-driven SPDX Project involving key industry experts, organizations, and open-source enthusiasts under the auspices of the Linux Foundation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The SPDX specification is recognized as the international open standard for security, license compliance, and other software supply chain artifacts as ISO/IEC 5962:2021.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] As of August 2025, the latest version of the standard has been 3.0.1.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The SPDX 2.x standard defines an SBOM document, which contains SPDX metadata about software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The document itself can be expressed in multiple formats, including JSON, YAML, RDF/XML, tag–value, and spreadsheet.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Each SPDX document describes one or more elements, which can be a software package, a specific file, or a snippet from a file.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Each element is given a unique identifier, and metadata for an element can refer to other elements.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] SPDX 3.0 allows users to communicate information at a much more granular level without having to package it as "envelope" data.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] A key design principle in SPDX 3.0 is that all elements may be expressed and referenced independent of any other element.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] This independence is required to support a variety of content exchange and analysis use cases and makes it easier to communicate single elements of interest.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The relationship structure has also been updated to be both more expressive and easier to understand compared to older versions of the specification.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The SPDX 3.0 data model is based on the Resource Description Framework (RDF).
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Data may be serialized in a variety of formats for storage and transmission, including formats defined in RDF 1.1 such as JSON-LD, Turtle (Terse RDF Triple Language), N-Triples, and RDF/XML.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The 3.0 specification introduced *profiles* to support the expansion of use cases beyond software, without increasing overall complexity.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Profiles allow users to define data for the use cases they need, while also increasing the amount of information that can be gathered directly from the SPDX data.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The first version of the SPDX specification was intended to make compliance with software licenses easier, but subsequent versions of the specification added capabilities intended for other use-cases, such as being able to contain references to known software vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Recent versions of SPDX fulfill the NTIA's 'Minimum Elements For a Software Bill of Materials'.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] SPDX 2.2.1 was submitted to the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in October, 2020, and was published as *ISO/IEC 5962:2021 Information technology — SPDX® Specification V2.2.1* in August, 2021.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Each license is identified by a full name, such as "Mozilla Public License 2.0" and a short identifier, here "MPL-2.0".
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Licenses can be combined by operators `AND` and `OR`, and grouping `(`, `)`.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] For example, `(Apache-2.0 OR MIT)` means that one can choose between `Apache-2.0` (Apache License) or `MIT` (MIT license).
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] On the other hand, `(Apache-2.0 AND MIT)` means that both licenses apply.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] There is also a "+" operator which, when applied to a license, means that future versions of the license apply as well.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] For example, `Apache-1.1+` means that `Apache-1.1` and `Apache-2.0` may apply (and future versions if any).
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] SPDX describes the exact terms under which a piece of software is licensed.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] It does not attempt to categorize licenses by type, for instance by describing licenses with similar terms to the BSD License as "BSD-like".
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] In 2020, the European Commission published its Joinup Licensing Assistant, which makes possible the selection and comparison of more than 50 licenses, with access to their SPDX identifier and full text.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The GNU family of licenses (e.g., GNU General Public License version 2) have the choice of choosing a later version of the license built in.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Sometimes, it was not clear whether the SPDX expression `GPL-2.0` meant "exactly GPL version 2.0" or "GPL version 2.0 or any later version".
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Thus, since version 3.0 of the SPDX License List, the GNU family of licenses got new names.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] `GPL-2.0-only` means "exactly version 2.0" and `GPL-2.0-or-later` means "version 2.0 or any later version".
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The SPDX license identifier can be added to the top of source code files as a short string unambiguously declaring the license used.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The `SPDX-License-Identifier` syntax, pioneered by Das U-Boot in 2013, became part of SPDX in version 2.1.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] In 2017, the FSFE launched REUSE, which provides tools to validate the comment and to efficiently extract copyright information.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] The SPDX license identifier is also used in a number of package managers such as npm, Python, and Rust cargo.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] SPDX license expressions are used in RPM package metadata in Fedora Linux, replacing the earlier use of the Callaway system.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/software-package-data-exchange] Debian uses a slightly different license specification.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] In computer security, a **vulnerability** is a flaw or weakness in a system's design, implementation, or management that can be exploited by a malicious actor to compromise its security.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Despite a system administrator's best efforts to achieve complete correctness, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs where the system does not behave as expected.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] If the bug could enable an attacker to compromise the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of system resources, it can be considered a vulnerability.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Insecure software development practices as well as design factors such as complexity can increase the burden of vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerability management includes identifying systems and prioritizing which are most important, scanning for vulnerabilities, and taking action to secure the system.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerability management typically is a combination of remediation, mitigation, and acceptance.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerabilities can be scored for severity according to the Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) and added to vulnerability databases such as the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) database.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] As of April 2026, more than 327,000 vulnerabilities had been recorded in the CVE database.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] A vulnerability is initiated when it is introduced into hardware or software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] It becomes active and exploitable when the software or hardware containing the vulnerability is running.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] The vulnerability may be discovered by the administrator, vendor, or a third party.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Publicly disclosing the vulnerability (through a patch or otherwise) is associated with an increased risk of compromise, as attackers can use this knowledge to target existing systems before patches are implemented.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerabilities will eventually end when the system is either patched or removed from use.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Despite a system administrator's best efforts, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] If a bug creates a security risk, it is called a vulnerability.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Software patches are often released to fix identified vulnerabilities, but zero-days are still liable for exploitation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerabilities vary in their ability to be exploited by malicious actors, and the actual risk is dependent on the nature of the vulnerability as well as the value of the surrounding system.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Although some vulnerabilities can only be used for denial-of-service attacks, more dangerous ones allow the attacker to perform code injection without the user's awareness.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Only a minority of vulnerabilities allow for privilege escalation, which is typically necessary for more severe attacks.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Without a vulnerability, an exploit typically cannot gain access.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] It is also possible for malware to be installed directly, without an exploit, through social engineering or poor physical security such as an unlocked door or exposed port.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Poor software development practices can affect the likelihood of introducing vulnerabilities to a code base.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Lack of knowledge or training regarding secure software development, excessive pressure to deliver, or an excessively complex code base can all allow vulnerabilities to be introduced and left unnoticed.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] These factors can also be exacerbated if security is not prioritized by the company culture.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Inadequate code reviews can also lead to missed bugs, but there are also static code analysis tools that can be used during the code review process to help find some vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] DevOps, a development workflow that emphasizes automated testing and deployment to speed up the deployment of new features, often requires that many developers be granted access to change configurations, which can lead to deliberate or inadvertent inclusion of vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Compartmentalizing dependencies, which is often part of DevOps workflows, can reduce the attack surface by paring down dependencies to only what is necessary.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] If software as a service is used, rather than the organization's own hardware and software, the organization is dependent on the cloud services provider to prevent vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Access control vulnerabilities enable an attacker to access a system that is supposed to be restricted to them, or engage in privilege escalation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] When the system fails to handle and exceptional or unanticipated condition correctly, an attacker can exploit the situation to gain access.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Configuration vulnerability come into existence when configuration settings cause risks to the system security, leading to such faults as unpatched software or file system permissions that do not sufficiently restrict access.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] A race condition—when timing or other external factors change the outcome and lead to inconsistent or unpredictable results—can cause a vulnerability.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Deliberate security bugs can be introduced during or after manufacturing and cause the integrated circuit not to behave as expected under certain specific circumstances.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Testing for security bugs in hardware is quite difficult due to limited time and the complexity of twenty-first century chips, while the globalization of design and manufacturing has increased the opportunity for these bugs to be introduced by malicious actors.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Although operating system vulnerabilities vary depending on the operating system in use, a common problem is privilege escalation bugs that enable the attacker to gain more access than they should be allowed.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Open-source operating systems such as Linux and Android have a freely accessible source code and allow anyone to contribute, which could enable the introduction of vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] However, the same vulnerabilities also occur in proprietary operating systems such as Microsoft Windows and Apple operating systems.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] All reputable vendors of operating systems provide patches regularly.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Client–server applications are downloaded onto the end user's computers and are typically updated less frequently than web applications.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Unlike web applications, they interact directly with a user's operating system.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Because they are inherently less secure than other applications, they are a leading source of data breaches and other security incidents.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] There is little evidence about the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of different cyberattack prevention measures.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Although estimating the risk of an attack is not straightforward, the mean time to breach and expected cost can be considered to determine the priority for remediating or mitigating an identified vulnerability and whether it is cost effective to do so.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Although attention to security can reduce the risk of attack, achieving perfect security for a complex system is impossible, and many security measures have unacceptable cost or usability downsides.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] For example, reducing the complexity and functionality of the system is effective at reducing the attack surface.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Successful vulnerability management usually involves a combination of remediation (closing a vulnerability), mitigation (increasing the difficulty, and reducing the consequences, of exploits), and accepting some residual risk.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Often a defense in depth strategy is used for multiple barriers to attack.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Some organizations scan for only the highest-risk vulnerabilities as this enables prioritization in the context of lacking the resources to fix every vulnerability.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Increasing expenses is likely to have diminishing returns.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Remediation fixes vulnerabilities, for example by downloading a software patch.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerability scanners are typically unable to detect zero-day vulnerabilities, but are more effective at finding known vulnerabilities based on a database.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] These systems can find some known vulnerabilities and advise fixes, such as a patch.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] However, they have limitations including false positives.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerabilities can only be exploited when they are active-the software in which they are embedded is actively running on the system.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Before the code containing the vulnerability is configured to run on the system, it is considered a carrier.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Dormant vulnerabilities can run, but are not currently running.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Software containing dormant and carrier vulnerabilities can sometimes be uninstalled or disabled, removing the risk.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Active vulnerabilities, if distinguished from the other types, can be prioritized for patching.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerability mitigation is measures that do not close the vulnerability, but make it more difficult to exploit or reduce the consequences of an attack.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Reducing the attack surface, particularly for parts of the system with root (administrator) access, and closing off opportunities for exploits to engage in privilege exploitation is a common strategy for reducing the harm that a cyberattack can cause.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] If a patch for third-party software is unavailable, it may be possible to temporarily disable the software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] A penetration test attempts to enter the system via an exploit to see if the system is insecure.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] If a penetration test fails, it does not necessarily mean that the system is secure.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Some penetration tests can be conducted with automated software that tests against existing exploits for known vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Other penetration tests are conducted by trained hackers.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Many companies prefer to contract out this work as it simulates an outsider attack.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] The vulnerability lifecycle begins when vulnerabilities are introduced into hardware or software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Detection of vulnerabilities can be by the software vendor, or by a third party.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] In the latter case, it is considered most ethical to immediately disclose the vulnerability to the vendor so it can be fixed.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Government or intelligence agencies buy vulnerabilities that have not been publicly disclosed and may use them in an attack, stockpile them, or notify the vendor.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] As of 2013, the Five Eyes (United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand) captured the plurality of the market and other significant purchasers included Russia, India, Brazil, Malaysia, Singapore, North Korea, and Iran.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Organized criminal groups also buy vulnerabilities, although they typically prefer exploit kits.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Even vulnerabilities that are publicly known or patched are often exploitable for an extended period.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Security patches can take months to develop, or may never be developed.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] A patch can have negative effects on the functionality of software and users may need to test the patch to confirm functionality and compatibility.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Larger organizations may fail to identify and patch all dependencies, while smaller enterprises and personal users may not install patches.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Research suggests that risk of cyberattack increases if the vulnerability is made publicly known or a patch is released.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Cybercriminals can reverse engineer the patch to find the underlying vulnerability and develop exploits, often faster than users install the patch.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Vulnerabilities become deprecated when the software or vulnerable versions fall out of use.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] This can take an extended period of time; in particular, industrial software may not be feasible to replace even if the manufacturer stops supporting it.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] A commonly used scale for assessing the severity of vulnerabilities is the open-source specification Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS).
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] CVSS evaluates the possibility to exploit the vulnerability and compromise data confidentiality, availability, and integrity.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] It also considers how the vulnerability could be used and how complex an exploit would need to be.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] The amount of access needed for exploitation and whether it could take place without user interaction are also factored in to the overall score.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Someone who discovers a vulnerability may disclose it immediately (full disclosure) or wait until a patch has been developed (responsible disclosure, or coordinated disclosure).
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] The former approach is praised for its transparency, but the drawback is that the risk of attack is likely to be increased after disclosure with no patch available.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Some vendors pay bug bounties to those who report vulnerabilities to them.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Not all companies respond positively to disclosures, as they can cause legal liability and operational overhead.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] There is no law requiring disclosure of vulnerabilities.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] If a vulnerability is discovered by a third party that does not disclose to the vendor or the public, it is called a zero-day vulnerability, often considered the most dangerous type because fewer defenses exist.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] The most commonly used vulnerability dataset is Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE), maintained by Mitre Corporation.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] This information is shared into other databases, including the United States' National Vulnerability Database, where each vulnerability is given a risk score using Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS), Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) scheme, and Common Weakness Enumeration.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] CVE and other databases typically do not track vulnerabilities in software as a service products.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Submitting a CVE is voluntary for companies that discovered a vulnerability.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] The software vendor is usually not legally liable for the cost if a vulnerability is used in an attack, which creates an incentive to make cheaper but less secure software.
[src:software-bill-of-materials-deep/vulnerability-computer-security] Some companies are covered by laws, such as PCI, HIPAA, and Sarbanes-Oxley, that place legal requirements on vulnerability management.
